t is meant by the term "video game" and the variety of modes of production within the medium. It moves on to a brief history of the video game, then applies the tools of film studies to look at the medium in terms of the formal aspects of space, time, narrative, and genre. The book also considers the video game as a cultural entity, object of museum curation, and repository of psychological archetypes. It closes with a list of video game research resources for further study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aVideo gameszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVideo gameszUnited States. 7aNON-CLASSIFIABLE.2bisacsh1 aBaer, Ralph H.1 aBaer, Ralph H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Steven L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlovin, Rochelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTews, Rebecca R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Mark J. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Mark J. P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/79148040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745131/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK